nd has immersed himself in the minutiae of its codes, reforms, political maneuverings, and culture. He demonstrates how an early modern empire made up of disparate lands connected solely by the feudal ties of a ruling family was transformed into a relatively unitary, modern, semi-centralized bureaucratic continental empire. This process was only derailed by the state of emergency that accompanied the First World War. Consequently, Deak provides the reader with a new appreciation for the evolving architecture of one of Europe's Great Powers in the long nineteenth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 4aAustria-Hungary. 4aAustria. 4aFrancis Joseph. 4aHabsburg Empire. 4aJoseph II. 4aadministration. 4abureaucracy. 4aconstitutional history. 4apolitical history. 4astate building. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804795937zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804795937423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804795937.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles